The '''SS ''Christopher Columbus''''' was an [[United States|American]] [[passenger ship|excursion liner]] on the [[Great Lakes]], in service between 1893 and 1933. She was the only [[whaleback]] ship ever built for passenger service. The ship was designed by [[Alexander McDougall (1845-1923)|Alexander McDougall]], the developer and promoter of the whaleback design.<ref name="ah">{{cite journal |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/it/2001/2/2001_2_24_print.shtml |title=You Call That Damn Thing a Boat? |journal=[[Invention and Technology Magazine|American Heritage of Invention & Technology]] |last=Ebeling |first=Charles W. |publisher=American Heritage Publishing |volume=17 |issue=2 |month=Fall |year=2001 |accessdate= August 31, 2007 |issn= 8756-7296 |oclc=11638224 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070929121045/http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/it/2001/2/2001_2_24_print.shtml <!--Added by H3llBot--> |archivedate=September 29, 2007}}</ref> 

''Columbus'' was built between 1892 and 1893 at [[Superior, Wisconsin]], by the [[American Steel Barge Company]]. Initially, she [[ferry|ferried]] passengers to and from the [[World's Columbian Exposition]]. Later, she provided general transportation and excursion services to various ports around the lakes.

At {{convert|362|ft|m|0}}, the ship was the longest whaleback ever built, and reportedly also the largest vessel on the Great Lakes when she was launched.<ref name = "sw1"/> ''Columbus'' is said to have carried more passengers during her career than any other vessel on the Great Lakes.<ref name="sw1"> {{cite web |first=Brendon |last=Bailod|title=Columbus information page |publisher=Ship-wreck.com |url=http://www.ship-wreck.com/shipwreck/projects/columbus/ |accessdate= March 25, 2008}}</ref> After a career lasting four decades, she was retired during the [[Great Depression]] and scrapped in 1936 by the Manitowoc Shipbuilding Company at [[Manitowoc, Wisconsin]].<ref name="bgsu">{{cite web |url=http://ul.bgsu.edu/cgi-bin/xvsl2.cgi |title=Christopher Columbus page of Vessel Index |work=Historical Collections of the Great Lakes |publisher=[[Bowling Green State University]] |accessdate= August 18, 2007}} Note: follow URL, then search by vessel name "Christopher Columbus" to find page with stats cited.</ref><ref name="mh-scrap">{{cite web |url=http://images.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/37051/data |work=[http://www.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca Maritime History of the Great Lakes] |title=The Great Lakes Vessel Extracts |first=William R. |last=McNeil|coauthors=Messmer, Jack |accessdate=August 18, 2007}}</ref>

==Background and proposal==
{{main|Whaleback}}
The history of the ''Columbus'' is linked with that of the whalebacks, an innovative but not widely accepted ship design of the late 1880s, and of their designer, [[Alexander McDougall (1845-1923)|Alexander McDougall]]. A [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[Immigration to the United States|immigrant]], Great Lakes [[captain (nautical)|captain]], inventor<ref name="about-whale">{{cite web
 |url=http://www.abouthegreatlakes.com/whale.htm
 |work=[http://www.abouthegreatlakes.com/ About the Great Lakes]
 |title=Remember the Whaleback Steamers
 |accessdate=August 18, 2007}}</ref> and entrepreneur, McDougall developed the idea of the whaleback as a way to improve the ability of [[barge]]s to follow a towing vessel in heavy seas.<ref name="ah"/> Whalebacks were characterized by distinctive [[hull (watercraft)|hull]] shapes with rounded tops, lacking conventional vertical sides. Waves thus broke across their hulls with considerably less force than when striking a conventional hull. Water could also flow around the rounded turrets which resembled [[gun turret]]s on contemporary warships; the superstructure and deckhouses were mounted on these turrets.<ref name = Duerkop>{{cite web | last = Duerkop | first = John | title = Some Marine Terminology | work = Research Resources | publisher = Marine Museum of the Great Lakes at Kingston | month = July | year = 2007 | url = http://www.marmuseum.ca/duerkop.html | accessdate = 2008-03-22 | archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080311063134/http://www.marmuseum.ca/duerkop.html <!--Added by H3llBot--> | archivedate = 2008-03-11 }} (definition 65, <U+2018><U+2019>Whaleback<U+2019><U+2019>).</ref> The rounded contours of whalebacks gave them an unconventional appearance,<ref name="ah"/>
<!--[[Image:Christopher Columbus whaleback Stereoview stern view.jpg|thumb|left|One half of a [[Stereoscopy|stereo]] view]]-->
and McDougall's ship and barge designs were received with considerable skepticism, resistance, and derision.<ref name="ah"/><ref name = Croil/> As they had porcine-looking snouts for bows, some observers called them "pig boats".<ref name = Duerkop/><ref name = Croil>{{cite book | last = Croil | first = James | title = Steam Navigation and Its Relation to the Commerce of Canada and the United States | publisher = Montreal News Company | location = Toronto | year = 1898 | oclc = 1082014 | pages = 362<U+2013>64 }} Google books has images of those pages in the chapter entitled [http://books.google.com/books?id=EEcvuKwJQnUC&pg=PA362&dq=%22The+Whaleback%22++%22Steam+Navigation%22 ''The Turret Steamship'']. Retrieved on 2008-03-26.</ref>

After McDougall was unable to persuade existing shipbuilders to try his designs, he founded the American Steel Barge Company in [[Superior, Wisconsin]] in 1888, and built them himself. McDougall actively promoted his design and company by sending the [[SS Charles W. Wetmore|SS ''Charles W. Wetmore'']] to London, and starting another shipyard in [[Everett, Washington]], which built the [[SS City of Everett|SS ''City of Everett'']].<ref name="wash">{{cite web
 |url=http://www.historylink.org/essays/output.cfm?file_id=7362
 |work=[http://www.historylink.org/ Washington State online history encyclopedia]
 |title=Charles W. Wetmore arrives
 |accessdate=August 18, 2007}}</ref> When the 1893 World's Columbian Exposition, to be held in [[Chicago, Illinois]], was in the planning stages, McDougall recognized another opportunity to publicize his design. The ''Columbus'', conceived as an elaborate [[ferry]], was intended to demonstrate that the whaleback design would work well in passenger service,<ref name="ah"/><ref name="about-whale"/> and would be able to travel at high speed.<ref name="mh_mReview"> {{cite web
 |url=http://images.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/26792/data
 |title=The Marine Record October 1, 1891
 |work=[http://www.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca Maritime History of the Great Lakes]
 |accessdate=August 18, 2007}}</ref> The ship's name honored the explorer [[Christopher Columbus]] as did the World's Columbian Exposition itself, timed to coincide with the 400th anniversary of his [[Voyages of Christopher Columbus#First voyage|first voyage]] to the New World.<ref name="about-whale"/>

==Construction and Columbian Exposition==
<!--[[Image:Christopher Columbus whaleback ccengine crop.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The ''Columbus'' was powered by two [[reciprocating engine|reciprocating]] [[triple-expansion engine|triple-expansion]] [[steam engine]]s.<ref name="mhgl-green"> {{cite web
 |url=http://www.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/Page.asp?PageID=3245
 |title=Green's Marine Directory of the Great Lakes |location=Cleveland |date= 1916 |pages=248| work=[http://www.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca Maritime History of the Great Lakes] |alast=Green |first=Fred W. |accessdate=August 18, 2007}}</ref>]]!-->
[[Image:Christopher Columbus whaleback build.jpg|thumb|Hull under construction, showing turrets on which the decks were placed]]
The World's Fair Steamship Company ordered the construction of the ''Columbus'' at an estimated cost of [[US$|$]]360,000. The job was undertaken at McDougall's American Steel Barge Company works in Superior, Wisconsin, starting in the fall of 1892.<ref name="seaC">{{cite news |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa4442/is_200410/ai_n16065472/pg_2 |title=Last of the Whalebacks |work=Sea Classics |year=2004 |last=Wilkens |first=Steven A. |accessdate=November 9, 2007}} {{Dead link|date=March 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  

The hull framing, which included nine [[Bulkhead (partition)|bulkheads]], was completed on September 13, 1892. The ship's propulsion mechanisms were next installed, consisting of a single four-bladed, {{convert|14|ft|m|0|sing=on}} diameter, {{convert|19|ft|m|0|sing=on}} pitch [[propeller]], the two [[steam engine#Multiple expansion engines|reciprocating triple-expansion steam engines]] (with three cylinders of {{convert|26|in|cm|0|sing=on}}, {{convert|42|in|cm|0|sing=on}} and {{convert|70|in|cm|0|sing=on}} diameters in a common frame with a {{convert|42|in|cm|0|sing=on}} stroke) manufactured by [[Samuel F. Hodge & Co.]] of [[Detroit, Michigan]], and six steel tubular return [[Scotch boiler]]s, ({{convert|11|ft|m|0|sing=on}} diameter by {{convert|12|ft|m|0|sing=on}} long), built by [[Cleveland Shipbuilding Company]].<ref name="mhgl-green">{{cite web
 |url=http://www.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/Page.asp?PageID=3245
 |title=Green's Marine Directory of the Great Lakes |location=Cleveland |year= 1916 |pages=248| work=[http://www.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca Maritime History of the Great Lakes] |alast=Green |first=Fred W. |accessdate=August 18, 2007}}</ref><ref name="scotch">{{cite web|url=http://www.steamboats.com/museum/engineroom6.html
 |title=Scotch Boiler description
 |work=History of the Steamboat
 |accessdate=October 16, 2007}}</ref> The rounded hull top was then added, followed by the six turrets, which were substantially larger than those employed on freighter whalebacks. The ship was launched on December 3, 1892, after which two [[superstructure]] decks were mounted on the turrets along the centerline of her hull to afford access to her two internal decks, one in the turrets and one in the hull below.<ref name="ah"/>

She was fitted out over the remainder of late 1892 and early 1893. Electric lighting was used, and she was elegantly furnished. Her grand saloon and skylighted [[promenade deck]] contained several fountains and a large aquarium filled with trout and other fish of the lakes. The cabins and public spaces were fitted out with oak paneling, velvet carpets, etched glass windows, leather furniture and marble. Shops and restaurants were provided for the passengers.<ref name="seaC"/><ref name="bookfair">{{cite book
 |url=http://columbus.iit.edu/bookfair/00114003.html 
 |chapter=Chapter XVIII. Transportation 
 |title=The Book of the Fair 
 |last=Bancroft
 |first=Hubert Howe
 |year=1893
 |publisher=The Bancroft Company, Publishers
 |edition=Cygne Noir
 |oclc=01412680}}</ref>

