}}
McDougall's American Steel Barge Company had committed in the contract that the ''Columbus'' would be built and delivered in three months, making her one of the fastest-built large ships of her time. The builders further promised rapid loading and unloading, predicting that the vessel would be able to embark 5,000&nbsp;passengers in five minutes, and disembark the same passengers in even less time. The ''Columbus'' was specified to be able run the {{convert|6|mi|km|0}} from the dock downtown to the fairgrounds at [[Jackson Park (Chicago)|Jackson Park]] and 64th Street in 20&nbsp;minutes.<ref name="seaC"/><ref name="dream">{{cite book
 |url=http://columbus.iit.edu/dreamcity/00034087.html
 |chapter=The Whaleback Steamship
 |title=The Dream City: a portfolio of photographic views of the World's Columbian Exposition
 |others=intr. by Halsey C. Ives
 |location=St. Louis, Missouri
 |publisher=N. D. Thompson Publishing Co.
 |year=1893
 |oclc= 2276578}}</ref>

McDougall set up another holding company, the Columbian Whaleback Steamship Company of [[Duluth, Minnesota]], to own and operate the ''Columbus''. She was [[ship commissioning|commissioned]] on May 13, 1893. Her first captain was John McArthur, who had captained other whalebacks for McDougall's firms, starting with the first powered whaleback, the ''Colgate Hoyt'', built in 1890. McDougall was quoted as having said to McArthur, "There is your steamboat; take her down to Chicago and make a success of her."<ref name="mhgl-JMacArthur"/>

[[Image:Christopher Columbus whaleback pass.jpg|thumb|right|A printed pass, signed by General Manager [[Alexander McDougall (1845-1923)|Alex McDougall]]]]
McArthur did just that. Painted in all white [[livery]], the ''Columbus'' made multiple round trips per day, sailing along the [[Lake Michigan]] shoreline from the [[Randolph Street (Chicago)|Randolph Street]]/Van Buren Street dock to the Jackson Park site of the World's Columbian Exposition's [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux arts]] "White City" exposition fairgrounds. A contemporary souvenir booklet called her "the greatest marine wonder of its time",<ref name="ah"/> and another publication dubbed her the "Queen of the Lakes."<ref name="CEbiblio_Seaboard">{{cite journal |title=Queen of the Lakes: Trip of the New Whaleback Propeller Christopher Columbus From Superior to Chicago....The Finest Excursion Steamer in America
 |journal=Seaboard
 |volume=5
 |pages=608&ndash;610
 |date=May 25, 1893}}</ref> She had an estimated capacity of 4,000&ndash;5,000 passengers on her four decks, but it was reported that she carried 7,000 on her [[maiden voyage]].<ref name="meteor">{{cite web
 |title=Other Famous Whalebacks
 |publisher = Superior Public Museums
 |url = http://www.superiorpublicmuseums.org/ssmeteor/Newother.htm
 |accessdate=March 25, 2008}}</ref> The [[Goodrich Transit Line]] steamer ''[[USS Blue Ridge (1918)|Virginia]]'' (later the USS ''Blue Ridge'') is said to have raced against her.<ref name="gsec">{{cite web
|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/agency/navy/lcc-19.htm
|title=LCC 19 Blue Ridge <U+2013> SP 2432 section
|work=globalsecurity.org forces and ships information
|accessdate=October 15, 2007}}</ref>

The ''Columbus'' carried between 1.7 and 2.0&nbsp;million passengers (sources differ) during the exposition, with only one fatality, a crew member.<ref name="mhgl-JMacArthur"> {{cite web
 |url=http://www.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/Documents/HGL2/default.asp?ID=s748
 |title=Marine Captain's Biographies, Volume II - Captain J. McArthur
 |work=[http://images.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/]
 |accessdate=August 18, 2007}}</ref> In recognition of that success, the commissioners of the exposition presented Captain McArthur with a gold watch engraved with a representation of the ship. McArthur went on to captain other whalebacks including the {{SS|Frank Rockefeller||2}}, which became the {{SS|Meteor|1896|6}}, the only whaleback surviving today.<ref name="mhgl-JMacArthur"/>{{clear}}

==Regular service==
[[Image:Christopher Columbus advertisement 1c.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Day trip advertisement, 1920s]]
<!--[[Image:Christopher Columbus whaleback Milw Broadway bridgedock.jpg||thumb|left|Crossing under the Broadway [[lift bridge]] in Milwaukee]]-->
After the exposition ended the ''Columbus'' entered passenger service, and an additional deck (third superstructure, fifth total) was added during the 1899&ndash;1900 winter season.<ref name="bgsu"/> Despite the ''Columbus''' success at the exposition, and McDougall's promotional efforts, the whaleback design never caught on. By 1900, the last whalebacks had been built in Superior: the ''Alexander McDougall'' in 1899 (the last powered ship), and the ''John Smeaton'', the last whaleback barge. The American Steel Barge Company was sold to the [[American Ship Building Company]], becoming their Superior Works, and switched to more conventional [[lake freighter|laker]] designs.<ref name="amship">{{cite web
 |url=http://www.shipbuildinghistory.com/history/shipyards/2large/inactive/amshipsuperior.htm
 |title=The American Ship Building Company (Superior WI) record of ships built
 |work=[http://www.coltoncompany.com/ Maritime Business Strategies, LLC aka Coltoncompany.com]
 |accessdate=February 5, 2008}}</ref>

In 1899 the ''Columbus'' was leased to and operated by the Goodrich Transit Line,<ref name="mh_captBioGoodrich">{{cite web|url=http://www.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/Documents/HGL2/default.asp?ID=s443
 |title=Marine Captains Biographies Vol 2 - Captain A. E. Goodrich entry
 |work=[http://images.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca]
 |accessdate=October 16, 2007}}</ref><ref name="bb1903listings">{{cite book 
 |url=http://images.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/63654/page/158
 |title=Blue Book of American Shipping: Marine and Naval Directory of the United States
 |year=1903
 |location=Cleveland, Ohio
 |publisher=Marine Review Publishing Co.
 |page=160
 |accessdate=August 18, 2007}} Listing shows the Columbus as "owned or managed by" Goodrich.{{cite book|url=http://images.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/63654/page/410
 |title=Blue Book of American Shipping: Marine and Naval Directory of the United States
 |year=1903
 |location=Cleveland, Ohio
 |publisher=Marine Review Publishing Co.
 |page=412
 |accessdate=August 18, 2007}} Image of the Columbus in Goodrich livery.{{cite book 
 |url=http://images.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/63654/page/424
 |title=Blue Book of American Shipping: Marine and Naval Directory of the United States
 |year=1903
 |location=Cleveland, Ohio
 |publisher=Marine Review Publishing Co.
 |page=426
 |accessdate=August 18, 2007}} This advertisement features the same image as above.</ref>
whose steamer ''Virginia'' had been a perennial racing rival.<ref name="ct">{{cite news
 |url=http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=9E02EFD71730E033A25756C0A9619C94679ED7CF
 |title=Ministers in a Steamboat Race.; It Was on Lake Michigan and They Rejoiced Greatly to Win.
 |work=[[The New York Times]]
 |date=July 5, 1896
 |accessdate=October 15, 2007
| format=PDF
| first=June
| last=30}} Tells of another racing exploit in 1896.</ref> She changed hands in 1905 to the Milwaukee & Chicago Transportation company &ndash; possibly a Goodrich holding company<ref name="bgsu"/> &ndash; and again in 1909 to Goodrich Transit Line.<ref name="bgsu"/> Her livery was at some point between 1906 and 1909 changed to a black hull with yellow accents, and she was placed in service on the route between Chicago and [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]]. The ''Columbus'' remained with the Goodrich line for several years. Although she was used for excursions elsewhere around the Great Lakes, her regular schedule was a daily trip to Milwaukee, leaving Chicago mid-morning, sailing to Milwaukee for a two-hour stopover, and then returning (''see advertisement right'').<ref name="schlitz">{{cite web
 |url=http://www.chiptin.com/schlitz/history3.htm
 |title=Excerpts from "Bucket Boy" by Ernest L. Meyer, 1947 
 |work=Joseph Schlitz Brewing Co.: A Chronological History 1881-1907
 |accessdate=October 19, 2007}}</ref> She made daily [[wiktionary:round trip|round-trip]] excursions from the Goodrich docks at the [[Rush Street Bridge]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Chicago: Growth of a Metropolis|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|author=Mayer, Harold M. and Richard C. Wade|year=1969|page=273}}</ref>

<!--[[Image:Christopher Columbus whaleback GoodrichDock.jpg|thumb|left|Stern view at the Goodrich Dock in Chicago]]-->
''Columbus'' had at least three accidents. In June 1895 she suffered an explosion caused by a steam pipe becoming disconnected while she was underway.<ref name="nyt">{{cite news
 |url=http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?_r=1&res=9901E5DB1039E033A25757C2A9609C94649ED7CF&oref=slogin
|title=Thirteen Were Injured
|work=The New York Times
|date=June 24, 1895
|accessdate=October 15, 2007
| format=PDF}}</ref> Accounts differ, but some claim that this happened during a race with her rival, ''Virginia''.<ref name="wp">{{cite web
 |url=http://www.daileyint.com/hmdpc/2005/06/public-transportation-and-sport-dont.html
 |title= Public Transportation and Sport Don't Mix - Especially with Steamboats
 |accessdate=October 15, 2007}} {{Dead link|date=March 2012|bot=H3llBot}} This blog cites ''The Washington Post''  [http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/279391492.html?dids=279391492:279391492&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&date=Jun+24%2C+1895&author=&pub=The+Washington&edition=&startpage=1&desc=BURST+A+STEAM+VALVE  archive] of the story.</ref> In July 1905, she collided with the [[schooner]] ''Ralph Campbell'' in the [[Chicago River]].<ref>{{cite web
 |url=http://images.maritimehistoryofthegreatlakes.ca/54700/data
 |title=Vessel Extracts: Campbell, Ralph
 |publisher=[[The Buffalo Evening News]]
 |date=July 25, 1905
 |accessdate=February 6, 2008}}</ref> On June 30, 1917, she was involved in her most serious accident, a collision with a [[water tower]]. The collision happened in Milwaukee while she was being maneuvered by [[tugboat|tug]]s away from her dock. The [[Milwaukee River]] current caught her, spinning her sideways, and her bow sheared off two legs of the Yahr-Lang Drug Company's water tower, toppling it and flooding ''Columbus''' decks with about {{convert|25000|USgal|l}}. The collision killed 16&nbsp;passengers and severely damaged her pilot house, putting her out of service for the rest of the year.<ref name="wisHist">{{cite web
 |url=http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/whi/fullRecord.asp?id=4685
 |title=Damaged "Christopher Columbus" Cruise Vessel
 |work=Wisconsin Historical Society site
 |accessdate=October 19, 2007}}</ref><ref name="wts"> {{cite web
 |url=http://www.eureka4you.com/watertowers/Stories.htm#Ship 
 |title=Ship hits water tower. (Milwaukee 1917)
 |work=Tower Accidents and other stories|accessdate=October 19, 2007}} Note, the site gives "unknown" for the attribution, but partially the same text is found at [http://www.boatnerd.com/news/archive/6-04.htm boatnerd.com] and gives "Great Lakes Ships We Remember" as a possible source.</ref>

[[Image:Christopher Columbus stability test.jpg|thumb|left|Stability testing]]
The ''Columbus'' was one of the first ships to be fitted with an on-board [[History of radio|radio]], installed by 1909, when she was allocated the call letters "KC".<ref name="wireless">{{cite book
 |url=http://earlyradiohistory.us/1909stat.htm
 |author=[[United States Navy|Navy Department]], Bureau of Equipment
 |title=List of Wireless Telegraph Stations of the World
 |location= Washington, D.C.
 |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office
 |chapter=List of Merchant Steamers and Private Yachts
 |date=September 1, 1908
 |accessdate=October 15, 2007}} The 1908 edition does not show her having assigned call letters so the inference is that she did not have one then.</ref> ''Columbus'' and the SS ''Chicago'' used radio to help coordinate the rescue of over 200 passengers from the Goodrich liner ''City of Racine'' when the ''Racine'' was disabled off [[Waukegan, Illinois]], in Lake Michigan.<ref name="wireless2">{{Cite journal
  | title = Notable Achievements of Wireless
  | journal = [[Modern Electrics]]
  | volume = 
  | issue = 
  | pages = 315
  | publisher = United States Early Radio History
  | date = September 1910
  | url = http://earlyradiohistory.us/1910note.htm  
| accessdate = March 25, 2008}}</ref>

In 1915, the [[SS Eastland|SS ''Eastland'']] capsized while docked in the Chicago River, with the loss of over 800 lives. Officials subsequently ordered many passenger ships to undergo stability testing, which the ''Columbus'' passed easily. Even with 7,500 sandbags (simulating passengers) piled on one side, and tugboats pulling in that direction, she listed only 12 degrees.<ref name="nyt stability">{{cite news
 |url=http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?_r=1&res=9B01EFDE1138E633A25755C0A96E9C946496D6CF
 |title=Redfield Halts Eastland Inquiry 
 |work=The New York Times 
 |date=August 6, 1915
 |accessdate=October 19, 2007
| format=PDF}}</ref><ref name="marMusCa">{{cite web 
 |url=http://www.marmuseum.ca/duerkop.html 
 |title= Some Marine Terminology <U+2013> by John Duerkop
 |work=Research Resources <U+2013> Marine Museum of the Great Lakes at Kingston|accessdate=October 19, 2007 
 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071108205516/http://www.marmuseum.ca/duerkop.html <!--Added by H3llBot--> 
 |archivedate=November 8, 2007}}  "Even with tugs trying to pull her over she hardly heeled"; quote attributed to ''Ships and Sailing'' May 1952.</ref> ''Columbus'' was featured at the [[Century of Progress]] exhibition in Chicago in 1932&ndash;33.<ref name="about-whale"/>
{{clear}}

==Disposition==
{{double image|right|Christopher Columbus whaleback Milw Broadway bridgedock.jpg|150|Christopher Columbus whaleback GoodrichDock.jpg|150|Passing under the Broadway lift bridge in [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], circa 1909|Stern view at the Goodrich docks, [[Chicago,  Illinois]] }}
The ''Columbus'' was taken out of service in 1933, and changed hands twice during the [[Great Depression]], in 1933 and again in 1934.<ref name="bgsu"/> She was scrapped in 1936 at the Manitowoc Shipbuilding Company in [[Manitowoc, Wisconsin]].<ref name="bgsu"/>

SS ''Christopher Columbus'' carried 1.7<U+2013>2 million passengers in her first year alone,<ref name = "ah"/><ref name="CEbiblio_p146">{{cite book
 |url=http://books.google.com/?id=F6cWRxU9go4C&pg=PA146&vq=SS&dq=%22ss+christopher+columbus%22 
 |page=146
 |title=The World's Columbian Exposition: A Centennial Bibliographic Guide
 |accessdate=October 15, 2007
 |location=Westport, Connecticut
 |publisher=Greenwood Press
 |year=1996
 |last=Bertuca
 |first=David J.
 |coauthors=Hartman, Donald K. and Neumeister, Susan M.
 |isbn=978-0-313-26644-7
 |oclc=28962073}}</ref> and is estimated to have carried more passengers than any other vessel on the Great Lakes.<ref name="about-whale"/> She was one of the most photographed passenger ships on the lakes, and [[souvenir]] [[postcard]]s of her are still widely available. One of her anchors, the design of which was patented by McDougall on February 3, 1891,<ref name="googlePatent">{{cite web |url=http://www.google.com/patents?id=b2Q_AAAAEBAJ
|title=Anchor Alexander McDougall
|work=[[Google Patents]] page
|accessdate=October 16, 2007}}</ref> is displayed at the [[Mariners' Museum]] in [[Newport News, Virginia]].<ref name="mmColl">{{cite web|url=http://collections.marinersmuseum.org/default.asp?IDCFile=DETAILS.IDC,SPECIFIC=30528
|title=McDougall Anchor Object Description page
|work=Mariners' Museum website, Collections section
|accessdate=October 16, 2007}}</ref>
